# External Libraries and Frameworks

This section explores external libraries and frameworks that may be used in the project. Each option is evaluated based on usability, scalability, learning curve, and accessibility support.

---

## Frontend Frameworks

### React.js
**Description:**  
React is a JavaScript library for building user interfaces using reusable components.

**Pros:**
- Component-based architecture improves code reuse
- Large community and ecosystem
- Excellent support for accessibility (ARIA, screen readers)
- Works well with modern UI libraries (Material UI, Tailwind)

**Cons:**
- Steep learning curve for beginners
- Requires additional libraries for routing and state management
- JSX syntax may be confusing initially

**Accessibility Notes:**
- Strong ARIA support
- Compatible with screen readers
- Encourages semantic HTML

---

### Angular
**Description:**  
Angular is a full-featured frontend framework developed by Google.

**Pros:**
- Built-in routing, forms, and HTTP support
- Strong TypeScript integration
- Clear project structure

**Cons:**
- Very steep learning curve
- Heavy framework for small projects
- More boilerplate code

**Accessibility Notes:**
- Good built-in accessibility tools
- Requires proper configuration for optimal results

---

## UI Component Libraries

### Bootstrap
**Description:**  
Bootstrap is a CSS framework for building responsive web interfaces quickly.

**Pros:**
- Easy to learn and use
- Responsive by default
- Large collection of prebuilt components

**Cons:**
- Limited customization without overriding styles
- Websites can look generic
- Less modern than newer frameworks

**Accessibility Notes:**
- Many components are keyboard accessible
- Requires care to ensure proper contrast ratios

---

### Tailwind CSS
**Description:**  
Tailwind is a utility-first CSS framework for building custom designs.

**Pros:**
- Highly customizable
- Encourages consistent design
- Smaller final CSS size

**Cons:**
- HTML can become cluttered with many classes
- Requires design decisions upfront

**Accessibility Notes:**
- Makes it easy to enforce contrast and spacing
- Developer is responsible for accessibility compliance

---

## Backend Frameworks

### Node.js with Express
**Description:**  
Express is a lightweight backend framework for building APIs using Node.js.

**Pros:**
- Simple and flexible
- Large ecosystem of middleware
- Fast development cycle

**Cons:**
- Less structured than full frameworks
- Requires manual setup for security and validation

**Accessibility Notes:**
- Accessibility handled mainly at frontend
- Can provide accessible error messages via APIs

---

### ASP.NET Core
**Description:**  
ASP.NET Core is a backend framework developed by Microsoft.

**Pros:**
- High performance
- Strong security features
- Excellent tooling support

**Cons:**
- Steeper learning curve
- Less flexible than lightweight frameworks

**Accessibility Notes:**
- Built-in support for accessibility standards
- Good integration with accessible frontend frameworks

---

## Diagramming & Documentation Tools

### Draw.io
**Description:**  
Tool for creating diagrams such as domain models and component diagrams.

**Pros:**
- Free and easy to use
- Integrates with GitHub
- Supports UML diagrams

**Cons:**
- Manual updates required
- Limited collaboration features

---

### Figma
**Description:**  
Figma is a collaborative UI design and prototyping tool.

**Pros:**
- Real-time collaboration
- Easy to share mockups
- Good accessibility testing features

**Cons:**
- Requires internet access
- Advanced features require paid plan

**Accessibility Notes:**
- Supports color contrast checks
- Useful for designing inclusive interfaces

---

## Summary

The selected libraries and frameworks will be chosen based on project requirements, team experience, and accessibility needs. Priority will be given to tools that support inclusive design, scalability, and maintainability.

